**Abstract:**
Major essay dated January 27, 1999 responding to John Paul II's encyclical Fides et Ratio. Argues that Aquinas's epistemology of faith as intellectual assent is modeled on Aristotle's speculative knowledge in Posterior Analytics rather than practical knowledge. Contends the Pope uses "philosophy" equivocally and cannot expect from philosophy the benefits he hopes for. Critiques the assumption that faith is knowledge in the speculative sense.

**AI Recommendation:** Major essay on faith-reason encyclical; see 99-Jan-1aquinas variants.

